# MCP vs Custom Tool Definitions

You've noticed something important! Let me break down the similarities and help you understand the relationship.

## Common Tool Definition Pattern

Most tool/function calling systems follow a similar structure because they're solving the same problem: **describing executable functions to an AI/system in a machine-readable way**.

### **Typical Tool Definition Structure**

```json
{
  "name": "function_name",
  "description": "What this function does",
  "parameters": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "param1": {
        "type": "string",
        "description": "What this parameter is for"
      }
    },
    "required": ["param1"]
  }
}
```

This pattern appears in:
- **OpenAI Function Calling**
- **Anthropic Tool Use (MCP)**
- **LangChain Tools**
- **Custom implementations**

## Why They're Similar

### **1. JSON Schema Foundation**

Most tool definitions use [JSON Schema](https://json-schema.org/) for parameter validation:

```json
// OpenAI
{
  "type": "function",
  "function": {
    "name": "get_weather",
    "parameters": {
      "type": "object",
      "properties": {
        "location": {"type": "string"}
      }
    }
  }
}

// MCP
{
  "name": "get_weather",
  "description": "Get weather data",
  "inputSchema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "location": {"type": "string"}
    }
  }
}
```

### **2. Common Requirements**

All tool systems need:
- **Name**: Unique identifier
- **Description**: For AI to understand when to use it
- **Parameters**: What inputs it accepts
- **Validation**: Type checking and constraints

## Key Differences: MCP vs Others

| Feature | MCP | OpenAI Functions | Custom Tools |
|---------|-----|------------------|--------------|
| **Protocol** | Standardized (JSON-RPC) | API-specific | Varies |
| **Transport** | stdio, HTTP, WebSocket | HTTP only | Your choice |
| **Discovery** | Dynamic (`tools/list`) | Static (per request) | Your design |
| **Lifecycle** | Persistent connection | Stateless | Your design |
| **Interop** | Cross-client compatible | OpenAI-specific | App-specific |

## Should You Adopt MCP or Keep Your Own?

### **Keep Your Custom Definition If:**

✅ You have a working system that meets your needs  
✅ You don't need cross-client compatibility  
✅ Your tools are tightly coupled to your application  
✅ You want full control over the protocol  
✅ Your definition has custom features MCP doesn't support

**Example custom tool:**
```typescript
// Your custom definition
interface MyTool {
  name: string;
  description: string;
  category: string;        // Custom field
  rateLimit: number;       // Custom field
  authenticate: boolean;   // Custom field
  parameters: JSONSchema;
  handler: (args: any) => Promise<any>;
}
```

### **Adopt MCP If:**

✅ You want your tools to work across multiple AI clients (Claude Desktop, IDEs, etc.)  
✅ You're building tools for others to use  
✅ You want to leverage existing MCP servers  
✅ You need standardized discovery and lifecycle management  
✅ You want to avoid reinventing the wheel

## Hybrid Approach: Bridge Pattern

You can **keep your existing tools** and create an **MCP adapter**:

```typescript
// Your existing tool definition
interface MyTool {
  name: string;
  description: string;
  parameters: JSONSchema;
  execute: (args: any) => Promise<any>;
}

// MCP Adapter
class MCPAdapter {
  constructor(private tools: MyTool[]) {}

  // Convert to MCP format
  async listTools(): Promise<MCPTool[]> {
    return this.tools.map(tool => ({
      name: tool.name,
      description: tool.description,
      inputSchema: tool.parameters
    }));
  }

  // Execute via MCP protocol
  async callTool(name: string, args: any) {
    const tool = this.tools.find(t => t.name === name);
    if (!tool) throw new Error(`Tool ${name} not found`);

    const result = await tool.execute(args);

    return {
      content: [{
        type: "text",
        text: JSON.stringify(result)
      }]
    };
  }
}

// Use it
const myTools = [myWeatherTool, myDatabaseTool];
const mcpServer = new MCPAdapter(myTools);
```

## Practical Recommendation

### **If you're starting fresh:**
→ Use MCP to benefit from standardization and ecosystem

### **If you have existing tools:**
→ Keep them, but consider adding an MCP adapter layer for interoperability

### **If you need custom features:**
→ Extend MCP or keep your custom definition with MCP as an optional export format

## Example: Supporting Both

```typescript
class UniversalTool {
  private definition: MyToolDefinition;

  // Your internal format
  getDefinition(): MyToolDefinition {
    return this.definition;
  }

  // Export as MCP
  toMCP(): MCPTool {
    return {
      name: this.definition.name,
      description: this.definition.description,
      inputSchema: this.definition.parameters
    };
  }

  // Export as OpenAI function
  toOpenAI(): OpenAIFunction {
    return {
      type: "function",
      function: {
        name: this.definition.name,
        description: this.definition.description,
        parameters: this.definition.parameters
      }
    };
  }

  // Execute (format-agnostic)
  async execute(args: any): Promise<any> {
    return this.definition.handler(args);
  }
}
```

**Bottom line:** The similarity is a feature, not a bug. It means you can easily bridge between systems. Keep what works for you, but consider MCP for interoperability when needed.
